Crimea and Sudetenland, the same fight?
BRUSSELS – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most severe example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has known since Nazi Germany's annexation of the Sudetenland in 1938.
It is certainly customary today to downplay the importance of the "Munich lessons" when referring to this episode, which saw Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier give in to Hitler's demands on Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of the invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might greatly regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – expulsion from the G8, for example – might seem laughable if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union to be the most grave catastrophe of modern times, the man striving relentlessly to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin shows.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have cost him almost nothing so far.
His initiative for a Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to rally a number of energy-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation forced it to reject the European Union's association agreement.
And now, the most precious geostrategic prize – Ukraine – may well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by former US National Security Adviser Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, with a Ukraine suborned and then subordinate, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the majority of Ukrainians have no desire to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president will now be a highly militarized state, akin to a Soviet Union without a communist party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction matches the degree of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Summits cancellations, trade agreement proposals, and other participation in as unproductive forums as the G8 will not be enough.
Only measures involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, let us remember, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin leave its expansionist trajectory.
What sanctions could it involve?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles to Russian transportation, as it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent the US from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial ships heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on Russia's economy – as well as on Putin's military claims – would be significant.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the 1936 Montreux Convention.
Turkey could thus counter Putin's justification for the annexation of Crimea – namely that he would preserve the Russian ethnic groups living there – by claiming it is protecting its Turkish-Tatar cousins, who, due to the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to make a U-turn in mid-air, heading to Kiev to provide support to the interim government.
The Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not tender either, could thus follow in his footsteps by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transports – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so they can return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good if Turkey could count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in case Russia tries to intimidate it.
Secondly, US President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia as he did on Iran over its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly crippled Iran's economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the US financial system to all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would create an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
The Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power was based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist agenda could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true drama in Putin's eyes, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was for China the most formidable geostrategic windfall imaginable.
In an instant, this empire that had taken several million hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners of China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia has seriously displeased China, as was evident at the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held after the war (this regional grouping brings together a number of former Soviet states sharing borders with China and the motherland).
Russia attempted to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
However, the Organization expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have been able to stand up to the Kremlin without China's support.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The true test of this Chinese assertion to be a genuine and responsible actor within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it side with Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also possible.
Each Russian leader could thus have their visas rejected or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, including those laundered by Putin's oligarch allies.
It's only when the pain becomes unbearable, and especially for the elites, that this kind of struggle led by Putin today will ultimately fail.
The price of inaction may prove to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, are counting on this promise from America to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Furthermore, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the explicit condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to rearm with nuclear capabilities (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase: "You had the choice between war and dishonor.
You chose dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are faced with a similar choice today.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the bold Putin will eventually serve them a new war.
